Scotland’s independent schools have many great academic results behind them, and it continues in 2018 with yet another series of outstanding exam results, which are further enhanced by individual and collective success in the field of sport, art, music and other efforts in the local environment.
With up to 30,000 students around Scotland, these schools, represented by The Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to deliver the best level of service to their students and parents.
The independent schools are trying to prepare their students for further and higher education, their chosen career and their place as global citizens.
As a sector of education that can compose and implement a tailored curriculum, we experience that modern languages remain a popular topic in schools.
Nelson Mandela said, “If you talk to a man in a language he understands, it hits his head.
If you talk to him in his own language, it hits your heart.”
It is an important reminder that we cannot just stick to English when we want to build relationships and trust among people from other countries.
We can look at the latest exam results this year, that language is the highest in the statistics with the most passed exams in the independent schools.
In total, 68 percent of the students who studied foreign languages received the high grade A.
The data collected by SCIS' 74 member schools showed that 72 percent of students received grade A in Mandarin, while 72 percent of those who studied German, 69 percent of those who studied French, and 63 percent of those who studied Spanish also received an A.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as important skills that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Language is now perceived as a choice of subjects at the same level as STEM subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in independent schools of thought and elsewhere.
A study conducted by the UK Commission for Employment and Skills in 2014 found that, among the reasons that employers were unable to occupy vacancies, 17% had to do with language skills.
Therefore, language skills are becoming more and more important in relation to preparing young people for their future careers.
More job opportunities will require language skills in the future, and these skills are essential in a globalized world.
No matter what career young people choose, if they have learned a different language, they have a great advantage in the future with a lifelong skill like this one.
The ability to communicate directly with people from other countries automatically gives a multilingual person a lead to the competitors.
According to a YouGov poll of over 4,000 respondents in the UK in 2013, 75 percent could not speak a foreign language well enough to conduct a conversation, and French is the only language spoken by a multi-digit percentage, 15 percent.
Therefore, it is important to invest in language education for those who are children today.
When you can speak multiple languages, especially languages from developing countries, you give children a better chance to find meaningful work.
In Scotland, there is a difference between schools in which languages are taught.
A number of schools focus on the more classic modern languages, while others teach languages that are expected to be most important to the UK when looking ahead to 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
No matter what your child is interested in, there will always be a number of languages to choose from in independent schools with teachers who are specialists in the field.
Scottish independent schools are dedicated to providing a learning environment that prepares children and gives them the skills needed to succeed, no matter what the future offers.
At present, it cannot be denied that languages continue to be truly important for the future of the country in a global business environment, and that must be reflected in education.
Modern languages should actually be considered "international communication skills".
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, this diversity and this award to Scotland’s youth.
We have to do it right.
