Update on algae blooming: Concentrations are reduced in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The latest report from the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission shows that there is a general decreasing algal concentration in parts of Tampa Bay.
According to the FWC, there are reports of widespread flowering in the area around Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier – suggesting that the concentration is decreasing.
The bloom of algae spreads over a coastline of 210 km from northern Pinellas County to southern Lee County.
There are smaller inflorescences about 16 km from the coast in Hillsborough County, but there are fewer than last week.
There have also been observed blooms in Pasco County.
Average concentrations in or at sea have been reported in Pinellas County over the past week, low to high concentrations in the sea out of Hillsborough County, background concentration to high concentrations in Manatee County, background concentration to high concentrations in or in the sea out of Sarasota County, background concentration in the sea
There are still reports of respiratory distress in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier.
No respiratory problems have been reported in northwestern Florida in the past week.
